one", "backgroundImage": "none"}, "imageCount": 0, "interactiveCount": 0}]}], "bodyStyles": {"fontSize": "17px", "fontWeight": "400", "fontFamily": "system-ui, -apple-system, \"system-ui\", \"Segoe UI\", Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif", "color": "rgb(26, 18, 16)", "backgroundColor": "rgb(253, 248, 242)", "display": "block", "position": "static", "borderTopColor": "rgb(26, 18, 16)", "borderRightColor": "rgb(26, 18, 16)", "borderBottomColor": "rgb(26, 18, 16)", "borderLeftColor": "rgb(26, 18, 16)", "borderTopWidth": "0px", "borderRightWidth": "0px", "borderBottomWidth": "0px", "borderLeftWidth": "0px", "borderTopLeftRadius": "0px", "borderTopRightRadius": "0px", "borderBottomLeftRadius": "0px", "borderBottomRightRadius": "0px", "paddingTop": "0px", "paddingRight": "0px", "paddingBottom": "0px", "paddingLeft": "0px", "marginTop": "0px", "marginRight": "0px", "marginBottom": "0px", "marginLeft": "0px", "textAlign": "start", "boxShadow": "none", "backgroundImage": "none"}, "htmlRect": {"x": 0, "y": 0, "width": 1440, "height": 2070.36, "bottom": 2070.36, "right": 1440, "area": 2981317.5}, "visibleText": "Copper Kettle Suppers Featured Recipe Ingredients Method Tips & Swaps About the Cook About the Cook TM Teodora Marchetti Cook, gardener, lifelong defender of a long, low oven. Teodora grew up in a third-floor flat above a fishmonger in Genoa, where the windows opened onto the smell of salt and basil and the kitchen never quite stopped working. Her grandmother kept a copper pot on the back burner from morning into evening, and the rule of the house was simple: nothing was rushed, nothing was wasted, and a beans-and-greens supper could carry a family through any kind of week. She moved to Edinburgh in her late twenties, trading the Ligurian coast for a stone tenement and a small back garden that now grows more rosemary than it has any right to. Her cooking sits somewhere between those two places \u00e2\u20ac\u201d Italian patience translated through a Scottish pantry. She writes about food the way she cooks it: slowly, plainly, and with a deep suspicion of any recipe that promises to be quick. A good braise forgives almost everything except impatience. Other Recipes in This Series Pork Belly with Fennel & Nduja Lentils Oxtail Rag\u00c3\u00b9 with Hand-Cut Pappardelle Salt Cod Brandade with Roasted Garlic Toast Chicken Thighs Braised in Verjuice & Bay Beef Cheeks with Soft Polenta & Gremolata Get in Touch For questions about this recipe, or to share a photograph of your own pot at the three-hour mark, write to teodora@copperkettlesuppers.test . \u00a9 2024 Copper Kettle Suppers \u00c2\u00b7 Recipes by Teodora Marchetti \u00c2\u00b7 teodora@copperkettlesuppers.test"}